I think you may have misunderstood the intention of @jdtournier's initial wording here. The l and m information indicates the parameterisation, i.e. just like the volume number (as an alternative parameterisation) does as well.  The bit between brackets is merely a description of the definition for said parameters.  E.g., for l=2 and m=-2, the definition of the function implies that you have to compute the imaginary part of the l=2 and m=2 SH.  The confusion might stem from the different use of m as a parameter: the first m (in this example -2) is a parameter of the "modified" SH basis, i.e. the one we define here in; whereas the second m is a parameter of the "standard" or "unmodified" SH that is used "within" the definition of the "modified" SH basis.  My wording here is on purpose a bit informal, but I suppose you get the point.

Just as a more formal example, I think one of the first ones (or at least one of the most often referred to) is Maxime's early PhD paper where he used symmetrical SH to model ADCs: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/mrm.20948 .  See equation 11 in there. It might not be exactly the basis used in mrtrix, but the general format of defining it is the same.  The original version of the documentation here defines the basis in function of volume number, similar to how Maxime's paper defines it in function of parameter "j".  The "j" parameter (or volume index) itself is defined in function of l and m (see the sentence before equation 11 in the paper). Finally there is equation 11 itself, which explains how this is then actually evaluated, and part of that is an "unmodified" SH evaluation; but for some values of m you have to take the real part, and for others the imaginary part; and this choice indeed depends on the sign of m.

So long story short: the original documentation here is very much in line to the way in which this is usually formally defined in the literature.  But the brevity of the documentation might lead to confusion.  I would therefore personally argue the brevity is the problem; but rather than making individual command documentation excessively long, it might be wise to keep it short on purpose, and include a reference to another place (this might e.g. be a documentation page), where there is enough space / flexibility / words to describe this in detail in a way that doesn't allow for confusion.  My final 2 cents would be that most users don't need this in detail in the command description; it's a lot of lines that they probably want to scroll past each time again just to look up the name of an option of said command, in my experience the most common use of the inline docs for many frequent users.  Users that require this description, are probably at least already trying to port information between software packages, or are implementing stuff on their own.  They would probably look into more detailed docs anyway, rather than going by a command description.

Lines 88-92 can go into `HibernateSearchHelper.createAndActivateSpan` as well, and even the `if (tracer != null)` check, all it needs is the `tracer` reference, which can be passed as an argument.
Another way to do this would be:

1. Make `createAndActivateSpan` an instance method instead of a static one
2. Add a `private final co.elastic.apm.agent.impl.ElasticApmTracer tracer` field to `HibernateSearchHelper` and a constructor to initialize it.
3. Add a `public static HibernateSearchHelper helper` field to `HibernateSearch5Instrumentation`
4. Add a constructor to `HibernateSearch5Instrumentation` that receives `co.elastic.apm.agent.impl.ElasticApmTracer` as an argument. This constructor will create and set the `HibernateSearch5Instrumentation#helper` field. We support such constructors in our instrumentation classes and we invoke them only once.

Separately: I think it might be neat to have a tool that does transforms *on schemas*, which we could use to (for example) drop all the 'rename's.  Dropping all the 'rename's in a schema would produce a topologically/cardinalically equivalent schema -- meaning we could map data described by one schema into the transformed schema guaranteed losslessly -- and then we could do things like easily have compact representations on the wire, using one schema, and flip it into more "debug-friendly" representations at will.

Naming here is very confusing, and it isn't helped by STIR's convention of using `additive_sino` for the normalised background, so I'm not sure if this is all correct. Let me try to write down what is happening.

`add_projdata_sptr` is set from `background projdata filename`. That is supposed to be the randoms.

If 3D,
1. `add_projdata_3d_sptr = add_projdata_sptr` (it's just saved, but the naming seems suspicious as we'd better be sure it is never used for `set_additive_proj_data_sptr`)
2. `back_projdata_3d_sptr` is filled with `add_projdata_3d_sptr ` (saved to `tmp_background_data.hs`). This will be the randoms.
3. `add_projdata_2d_sptr` = `SSRB(add_projdata_3d_sptr)`, i.e. effectively 2D randoms
4, `back_projdata_2d_sptr` is filled with `norm*SSRB(add_projdata_3d_sptr)` (and saved to `tmp_background_data_2d.hs`)

if 2D
1. `add_projdata_2d_sptr = add_projdata_sptr`
2. `back_projdata_2d_sptr` is currently not set at all (commented out)

Then
```
 if (export_2d_projdata)
        back_projdata_sptr = this->back_projdata_2d_sptr;
    else
        back_projdata_sptr = this->back_projdata_3d_sptr;
```
I can't understand see why the `export_2D` variable is used (the name doesn't seem to fit its purpose). I guess you use it to distinguish between 2D and 3D processing. a bit confusing.

Finally,
```
    iterative_object->get_objective_function_sptr()->set_additive_proj_data_sptr(this->back_projdata_sptr);
```
This will only work if `back_projdata_sptr` is the "normalised background"., but that seems ONLY the case if 3D and `export_2D==true`.

This seems therefore incorrect in some cases, but we might have been lucky.

In any case, we need to clear up the terminology here to avoid this type of confusion. I think we should stick to the SIRF convention: `background` would correspond to randoms, `add_projdata` should correspond to normalised `background` (it seems the reverse now, except for the parsing)

I saw now benefit of having separate CONFIGURE and PATCH steps without some extra power of reverting the state on-failure.

But that said, I introduced a generic "apply patchfiles" step that abstracts the `PATCH_COMMAND` nicely. I'll post this shortly.

In MS Excel, every double quote you entered will be "translated" to **two** double quotes in raw format.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/35756209/60391289-96ed4600-9b1d-11e9-903d-7bd3996ce583.png)

So `""Tora, S/O," Douya, T."` in excel means `"""""Tora, S/O,"" Douya, T."""` in RAW form.

- Because certain characters are added, such as `,` and `"`, the entire string will be enclosed with a double-quote.
- For each double-quote entered in Excel, it will be **two** double quotes in RAW form.

For `Borex T"ony Tong` in Excel --> `"Borex T""ony Tong"` in RAW form.

We are dealing with RAW form here.

Apologies, I'm not sure I explained this very clearly above. What I meant to say is that there is no problem with using `vw` when setting a `max-width`. Viewport units are widely supported and implementation across browsers is consistent, so their behaviour is stable and predictable. Thus, we should not be reluctant to use them where necessary. Setting a `max-width` of `100vw` will not cause a scrollbar to appear. As I was trying to explain above, the only situation where unwanted scrollbars can occur is when setting `100vw` as **width**. `width` and `max-width` have quite distinct behaviours, and when using `max-width` with `100vw`, the computed width of the element will never be higher than the width of its parent elements, so no chance of scrollbars. In this particular situation, setting a `max-width` of `100vw` for the sticky warning will ensure that, no matter what styles are applied to its parent elements, this element will never overflow the viewport. Because this is a sticky component, it is crucial that we ensure users are able to close it, so we need to be extra careful that the close button never disappears. The problem with avoiding `vw` and instead unsetting the `min-width` and `overflow-x` on the body element is that as soon as someone sets another `min-width` further up the tree, this component will break again. This is a codebase with a lot of contributors, and even the seasoned ones don't know the reasoning behind every line of code by heart. And we can't hope to be aware of every single line that's added every day. So even though we're all doing our absolute best here, with this sort of issue it pays to take a preventive stance. The other problem with unsetting the overflow on the body is that as soon as we do that we will have to quickly fix a bunch of components causing horizontal scrolls, not only on the `wp-admin` side but on the block editor as well. For instance, this is the recent implementation of the columns block placeholder, on a 700px viewport at 250% zoom: While I agree these problems definitely need to be addressed, they are out of scope for this PR.

@evanlinjin in the current state `doneMx` is really needed. It's purpose here is to separate read/close opeartions, no matter how strange this may sound to you, this is what was intended. We have read operation in `IsClosed` and we have close operation in `Close`. We need to close the `done` channel right after the socket is closed, but while it is in the process of closing, we don't want read operations to occur. Simply, the channel won't get closed in time, thus `IsClosed` will return false leading to the error being returned from `Serve`. Removing `doneMx` causes the data race in this particular case. At the moment, IntelliJ imposes two limitations on the directory layout of modules, particularly:

- The root path of a module cannot overlap with another module's root path
- A module's source and test files must be in folders underneath the configured root path

I checked sbt-projectmatrix's sources and it does provide any possibility to customise the platform paths.

At least for Seed we can partially fix the IDEA project generation with the following settings:

```
[module.pine]
root = "src/main/scala"
...
 
[module.pine.jvm]
root = "src/main/scala-jvm"
...
 
[module.pine.js]
root = "src/main/scala-js"
...
```

This satisfies the first requirement from above, but the test folder is not underneath the root path anymore. The project generation still works as expected and IntelliJ will now hide the tests.

I am fine with the new file structure given that developers will not notice anything unless they want to write test cases. Hopefully, IntelliJ's module restrictions will be lifted in the future.

This would also allow us to change the `NewStore` factory function to accept variadic parameters. It could look like this:
`func NewStore(options Options, backends ...gokv.Store) (Store, error)`.

Also, it's currently not optional to use this type for convenience, because the current `NewStore` function takes an `Options` argument which only contains `Backend`s instead of `gokv.Store`s. In this case using `MustBackend()` is required and leads to some extra lines of code.

This also feels like a level of indirection. It's easier for a package user to understand if he can create a combiner directly with multiple stores.

I don't think we should add a direct dependency on this package, as it's not required for the library to work.

Applications using this library will have to bump the stringstream package in their own lockfiles to get the fixed version; bumping it in the lockfile in this repo only affects the version used when developing the library itself:

https://yarnpkg.com/blog/2016/11/24/lockfiles-for-all/

> When you publish a package that contains a `yarn.lock`, any user of that library will not be affected by it. When you install dependencies in your application or library, only your own `yarn.lock` file is respected. Lockfiles within your dependencies will be ignored.

I was surprised to discover that Yarn has no way to upgrade indirect dependencies (https://github.com/yarnpkg/yarn/issues/4986). Presumably that's what prompted you to add the direct dependency?

Given all that: I think leaving `package.json` as is and running `yarn upgrade request`, or even `yarn upgrade`, would be a better was to resolve https://github.com/intercom/intercom/issues/143632.

I see that you use a similar error handling statement above in `ip(...)`. Perhaps consider grouping the error handling statements in `ip()` and `historical_data()` into a single `try_request(...)` method a la: 

```
def try_request(func, *args, **kwargs):
  try:
    resp = await func(*args, **kwargs)
  except ExchangeDataAccuracyError as e:
    return {"error": "exchange_data_accuracy_error", "description": str(e)}, 400
  except NetworkError as e:  # pragma: no cover
    return {"error": "network_error", "description": str(e)}, 400
  except Exception as e:  # pragma: no cover
    return {"error": "server_error", "description": str(e)}, 400 
```
so `ip()` now invokes:
```
resp = await try_request(get_exchange_info, exchange=exchange)
```

and `historical_data()` now invokes:
```
resp = await try_request(get_historical_data, **request)
```

I'd advocate still simplifying these 3 lines:

```python
for missing_init in identify_missing_init_files([target_workdir]):
  Path(missing_init).touch()
```

Couple reasons I'm advocating for this:
1. Consistency with how we handle missing `__init__.py` in the rest of the codebase.
1. Less code.
1. Makes the `Path()` creation simpler. `identify_missing_init_files()` will return back the whole file path, so you don't need `os.path.join` anymore.

--

As an aside, if you were to keep this original version, you could use `pathlib.Path`'s use of the `/` operator in place of `os.path.join`, like this:

```python
(Path(root) / dirname / '__init__.py').touch()
```

The syntax is supposed to mirror how directories are in posix systems, e.g. `hello/world/test.py`.

I didn't talk, but maybe I should've, about the Active Record pattern ‚Äîthe one we use in Rails‚Äî.

The Active Record pattern is a favorite for a lot of ORMs and it makes the model responsible of its own data layer abstraction as well. So you have things like (Rails' ActiveRecord ORM):
```rb
user = User.find_by(name: 'Lee')
user.name = 'Lee üßõüèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è'
user.save
```

Separating the business logic from the data layer would be the Data Mapper pattern, which may not look as pretty, but is more easily optimizable.

There's no silver bullet and in the end what matters is that you know when to use what.

The tests get a little weird with the scoped session, but I didn't want to have the tests all the sudden using the internal _Session API. I say weird because, the `.create` method on the obj uses the scoped session internally. Then the test uses a second scoped session to do the query for asserting. The `create` method no longer returns anything, because the `obj` that is created inside the session is disconnected once the create returns. Therefore, we can't do anything with the return any way. I would argue this is cleaner - if the obj is created, it is just created and then it is the DB responsibility to manage the lifecycle. If we then want to access the obj, we need to query for it.

Consider the following:

```haskell
type family AlwaysStuck :: Symbol
```

when we don't have the `IfStuck "NOT_A_REAL_SYMBOL"` case, the following:

```haskell
type Bug = IfStuck AlwaysStuck (TypeError (Text "Stuck!")) (Pure (() :: Constraint))

foo :: Bug => ()
foo = ()
```

somehow the type family evaluates to `() :: Constraint`, and therefore `foo` doesn't the `Stuck!` type error. But `AlwaysStuck` is, as it implies, *always stuck.*

What's going on here? *The kinds matter.* `IfStuck` won't even compare against the `T1` or the `9999999999999` cases, because neither of those things has kind `Symbol`. And so it will just boop out the `IfStuck a b c = Eval c` case!

No, you cannot do this. This status check shouldn't have any side effect. Also, just imagine if the user never calls to check the status of restoration, then the restoration will never be completed.

But the point you raised is valid. There is a way out. During the restoration, if no frontend is enabled, the revert won't be needed in the controller since it's mainly used to refresh the cache of the block device (frontend). Also, the currently logic makes replicas automatically revert to the restored snapshot, which will cause problems anyway if the controller's frontend is still up.

So we can add a few constraints to make it work:
1. If the controller's frontend is up, no restoration is allowed.
2. If a restoration is in progress for any replica, `start-frontend` of the controller is not allowed. For this purpose, replicas need to reports if it's restoring or not.

Since replicas revert to the newly restored snapshot automatically, after the restoration is completed, the frontend can be started again and the volume should contain the restored volume content.

My first thought was it's not intuitive how to use these options, since e.g. `(sending_timeout => 1, timeout => 3)` and `(sending_timeout => 3, timeout => 1)` would both have the same global timeout, but different "no activity" timeouts. Since they're added, it's not clear what `sending_timeout` measures, i.e. what will happen after 1s in the first case or 3s in the second.

Might be less confusing to just have one option for the global timeout (perhaps repurposing `timeout` for it), since these may not work as one might expect. The `LWP::UserAgent` `timeout` doesn't seem to be something we particularly need to configure separately - it aborts the request "if no activity on the connection to the server is observed for timeout seconds," but we mainly just want to ensure the entire request returns within X seconds. So `LWP::UserAgent` `timeout` can just be set to the same value as the global `timeout` (or even timeout / 2 if we want to abort early).

I dont think we want to use `ConstLabels` here, as that means those labels will always be applied and wont allow us to override them, for example for other `type:` labels, (like `evaluation`).

From the prom [go docs](https://godoc.org/github.com/prometheus/client_golang/prometheus#Opts):

>  // ConstLabels are used to attach fixed labels to this metric. Metrics
    // with the same fully-qualified name must have the same label names in
    // their ConstLabels.
    //
    // ConstLabels are only used rarely.

Instead, I think we want to use the labels at time of use, so that `cacheHitTotal` and `cacheMissTotal` will be available package wide, but when you use them you'll add the labels, ex:

```go
cacheHitTotal.WithLabelValues("type", "flag", "cache", "memory").Inc()
```

Then for when we add evaluation cache, it will be like:

```go
cacheHitTotal.WithLabelValues("type", "evaluation", "cache", "memory").Inc()
```

See: https://godoc.org/github.com/prometheus/client_golang/prometheus#CounterVec.WithLabelValues

- You don't need always to side-load the app to perform dyn. ana. the app might be installed already or you need to extra repackage it (for non-rooted) devices.

1. This tutorial is for the average beginning developer. Since the smallest hard drive one can easily buy these days is hundreds of GB and sufficiently large USB flash drives are frequently given away for free, I don't expect the [5GB requirement ](https://docs.anaconda.com/anaconda/install/) to be a problem for the average beginning developer. I'm not saying that this is not a problem for anyone on any platform - I've had a hard time staying under a 2GB quota on a remote server I wanted to use for SciPy development - but that Anaconda serves a wide audience. I noticed that Rust is light touch here and I think it's intentionally: Once an RFC is merged and "active", a tracking issue is opened in the relevant repo, and that's where all the implementation details and subsequent attention is directed. Which makes sense to me. The RFC itself is therefore is not a full spec and something that should be tracked. Instead becomes something of a historical artefact. 

They don't even have a state for Active/Inactive in Rust, if RFC1 is replaced by RFC2, they simply put a comment in RFC1 that it's been superseded by RFC2 and link to it.

To me, this makes sense, as you ultimately track the actual issues you have in your sub-team's repo.

Don't worry about it, the framework will close all the sessions in postprocess_vm, so you wouldn't need to close it in case.

```
def postprocess_vm(test, params, env, name):
    """
    Postprocess a single VM object according to the instructions in params.
    Kill the VM if requested and get a screendump.

    :param test: An Autotest test object.
    :param params: A dict containing VM postprocessing parameters.
    :param env: The environment (a dict-like object).
    :param name: The name of the VM object.
    """
    vm = env.get_vm(name)
    if not vm:
        return

    # Close all SSH sessions that might be active to this VM
    for s in vm.remote_sessions[:]:
        try:
            s.close()
            vm.remote_sessions.remove(s)
        except Exception:
            pass
```

In fp-ts lingo this is just a `ReaderTaskEither`: 3 effects (function/input, async, error) stacked. `fetch` is just the old avenger lingo, introduced a few years ago when describing the API for the first time with Giulio (see https://github.com/buildo/avenger#fetch), in any case not something particularly meaningful or essential.

My opinion at the moment is: when this is backported to fp-ts v2 (should happen soon), creating and handling `ReaderTaskEither`s is going to be cheaper and more intuitive (no `class` wrapping), so the Fetch name could just be dropped in favor of `ReaderTaskEither`.

Do you have any suggestions in the meantime?

Regarding:
> So the Fetch concept is not strictly related to fetching some data, but to a more general remote call

I'd say not even to the "remote call" part. This is probably not obvious from these docs, but a query is characterized by one or more of the 3 effects described above. E.g. we use it to access `localStorage`, which is only effectful in the sense of IO (sync) and possibly Either (validation of the contents), but definitely not "remote"

It's not clear to me if the attribution of the approach to Jonker--Volgenant is as precise as we may wish: They themselves note that shortest path approaches date back to Tomizawa (1979, doi 10.1002/net.3230010206), and in *Assignment Problems*, by Rainer Burkard, Mauro Dell'Amico, Silvano Martello, the algorithm implemented here is simply referred to as "Shortest_Path" (see Algorithm 4.9, Section 4.4). Most of the work done in Jonker--Volgenant is related to preprocessing and initialization -- coming up with a good partial solution before moving to shortest path searches -- but that hasn't been included in the implementation at hand (and I'm not saying I think it should be). So, is there anything in Jonker--Volgenant's approach that mean that we shouldn't just attribute the approach to any of the earlier references?

It should be truncated (`.rounded(.down)`?) instead of `rounded()`.

[The Date Formatting Guide](https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/documentation/Cocoa/Conceptual/DataFormatting/Articles/dfDateFormatting10_4.html#//apple_ref/doc/uid/TP40002369-SW13) said:
> The format string uses the format patterns from the Unicode Technical Standard #35. 

And [the Unicode Technical Standard #35](http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr35/tr35-31/tr35-dates.html#Date_Field_Symbol_Table) said:

|Field|Sym.|No.|Example|Description|
|-----|----|---|-------|-----------|
|second|S|1..n|3456|Fractional Second - **truncates** (like other time fields) to the count of letters. (example shows display using pattern SSSS for seconds value 12.34567)|

`DateFormatter` rounds sub-millisecond and also caused #192.
I filed this behavior and document inconsistency as a bug: https://bugs.swift.org/browse/SR-11049

For now, this implementation rounds sub-millisecond the same as `DateFormatter`, but this may have to be fixed.

The only non-hacky way to find a dynamic ID is to query it from the *stack*. The stack should be the entry point for basically any checking of stack-managed resources, since that is the only truly constant thing in many cases.

e,g,
```python
import boto3

# these would come from parameters in a real solution
STACK_NAME = 'ci-lambda-aws-auto-off-dev-awsautooff'
RESOURCE_LOGICAL_ID = 'StateMachine'


cloudformation = boto3.client('cloudformation')

# list ALL resources in stack
all_resources = cloudformation.describe_stack_resources(StackName=STACK_NAME)['StackResources']

# find all state machines (you could keep this more dynamic and generic by just monitoring *all* found state
# machines in a stack, rather than finding one by name)
all_state_machines = [l for l in all_resources if l['ResourceType'] == 'AWS::StepFunctions::StateMachine']

# find the specific state machine based on the "logical" name (i.e. the name given in the template)
named_state_machine_resource = [l for l in all_state_machines if l['LogicalResourceId'] == RESOURCE_LOGICAL_ID][0]

# find the ARN from the resource dict
state_machine_arn = named_state_machine_resource['PhysicalResourceId']

print(state_machine_arn)


```

As the previous poster said, the problem here is not that the CSP version is not working, but that each CSP violation generates a report to your configured `report-uri`,  and as the check for CSP is done in the main body, it is executed each time the JS file is loaded by a browser and generates a CSP report violation.
Most CSP reporting tools can filter CSP reports based on content, but as this is reported as an inline code execution, location is always line 1 / character 1, so you can not differentiate between this "legit" violation or another violation, making the reporting quite useless.

I would love to have a way to say that I am using a strict CSP policy and I never want this executed, opting for the slower path.

Please avoid building your own `Reflections` object here. You can retrieve a `org.terasology.module.ModuleEnvironment` (it's a gestalt-module class, not in the engine) from the `ModuleManager` (using `ModuleManager.getEnvironment`) in the context and use that instead. You can load the `ModuleManager` by creating a `@In ModuleManager moduleManager` field or by loading it through `context.get(ModuleManager.class)` if you have access to a context.

`ModuleEnvironment` already contains a `Reflections` object (and wrapper methods that delegate to that object) built over the engine and all loaded modules, so building the new `Reflections` object here is slow and completely unnecessary, and also may not encompass all loaded modules -- the reason for the missed components @Cervator was talking about.

Hmm. That's not how I read the process. To me, it is indeed implied, because when you republish **the same** technical report, the latest publication replaces the previous ones (which are merely kept around for archival and documentation purposes). This is where the implication is: when you republish a report, this is always with the intent of replacing (i.e. superseding) previously published versions of the same report. And there isn't really an undo or a way to grant exceptions here; if you have published a document as CR, and decide that you liked the previous WD better, you cannot undo the publication of the CR (although you can publish a new WD that replaces the CR and has the same content as the old one). Similarly, If you have published a second REC of the same technical report, you cannot "un-supersede" the first REC without republishing it on top of the second one. In other words, a single technical report only has one latest version, and all the non-last versions are superseded by it.

> You can still go ahead and use CSS if you want to, so it becomes a more flexible solution.

That means we're providing an extra way to do a thing we don't encourage in the first place. I get what you're saying about discouraging CSS usage, but if they get to the point of needing _custom_ values (which is what our `margin` prop would allow), they've got to the point of just using CSS anyway. I understand that we're providing an "easier" (though barely) way to style a component, but it's an easier way to do something you don't want to encourage.

From what I can tell the two _common_ scenarios are:

* use the default theme values you should be supplying with your theme
* use no margin because it's a solo icon

Anything else should be a rarity and it's fine to one-off it. Or maybe we should have multiple theme values. Overriding the defaults being discouraged is fine, but if that's the case why offer an override prop?

I should be clear: I'm talking about just the `margin` prop. For things like colour, which are pretty fundamental to an icon and are encouraged/likely to be changed by the user, it's fine to have a prop for it.

## Step 3: Add HTML document structure Great job opening a pull request @designedchen! I've gone ahead and closed your [previous issue](https://github.com/designedchen/intro-html/issues/1). This pull request contains some content, but it doesn't have any of the HTML structure that tells a browser how to structure the content. All pages created with HTML must contain tags that identify it as such. The tags look like this: ```html The HTML content goes here. ``` You may notice two copies of the HTML tag, and two copies of the body tag. We call these the _opening_ and _closing_ tags. So there will be times where a static type checker will need additional information about the types of variables beyond the annotations in function/method argument and return types (e.g. one of the issues in `syft/grid.py` was `"error: Need type annotation for 'tag_counter'"`). If we want to be able to run mypy without errors on the codebase, there are two paths: 

* Add an annotation in variable definitions where needed such that mypy can infer the types of variables it doesn't yet understand (the approach I took in this diff), or

* Add the same type information in a comment e.g. `tag_counter = Counter()  # type: CounterType[int]`

Either is a fine solution, though the latter might be a bit more approachable for a contributor who is familiar with Python but not yet type annotations. I didn't take this path as there is [a linting check](https://github.com/OpenMined/PySyft/blob/dev/.pre-commit-config.yaml#L21) disallowing type information in comments. We _could_ disable that if it's preferable - what do you think?

The convention currently seems to be that the `flang` versions' first component is `'flang'`,  so make this a bit more clear:

```python
    and spec.version[0] != 'flang'
```

Or, possibly cleaner but currently kind of weird looking:
```python
    and 'flang' not in spec.version.version
```

The versions are compared (mostly) the way RPM compares versions: split into a tuple on punctuation and at alpha/numeric boundaries, and compare the resulting tuples lexicographically.  Using `[]` on a `Version` gives you the components of that split.  `spec.version[0]` is the `'flang'` part you want.  `spec.version.version` gets you the tuple itself, but it's sadly not very well named... it should really be something like `'parts'` to make the second case above read better.

A larger question is why the flang versions aren't just suffixes of the LLVM base version, e.g. `3.6.0-flang-20180921`. That would make them compare properly with the other versions so we wouldn't have to special case them here.  That's more of a question for @tinlun or @gklimowicz and can be fixed later.

`initial` is the actual size of the table since there is no way to grow the table.

Per https://webassembly.org/docs/modules/#table-section,

> In the MVP, tables can only be resized via host-defined APIs (such as the JavaScript WebAssembly.Table.prototype.grow). A grow_table may be added in the future :unicorn:. In either case, table growth is guaranteed to fail if attempting to grow past the declared maximum. As with linear memory, when a maximum is declared, implementations should (non-normative) attempt to reserve virtual memory up to the maximum size. While failure to allocate the initial memory size is a runtime error, failure to reserve up to the maximum is not. When a maximum memory size is not declared, on architectures with limited virtual address space, engines should allocate only the initial size and reallocate on demand.

To avoid confusion, it may be worth further enforcing that maximum is either omitted or equal to initial.

I did some local test, the proposed pull request could not work correctly. If you start two provider and a consumer, you can see that cpu usage is not being sent from provider to consumer.

I agree with @guohao that, we need to call the CpuUsageService remotely to add listener rather that `new` directly, and if there are multiple providers, we have to call the addListener method for each provider. 

The problem is the StatisticsLoadBalance is a bean managed by Spring, so it is impossible to get the provider ip addresses when initializing StatisticsLoadBalance class. So we have to delay the call the addListener to the `doSelect` method.

To obtain a proxy for remote service, you may checkout `org.apache.dubbo.monitor.dubbo.DubboMonitorFactory#createMonitor`, there are some example code.

Since it is lazy to obtain the cpu usage, the load balance may not working very well during the initial period of time (lack of cpu usage stat), so there should be some fall back strategies, once the cpu stat are collected, the stat based load balance can be activated.

I just pushed several updates to the RFC to address this.

I flipped the recommendation around. It now leaves the `&` background operator behavior as is, which matches the default `Start-Job` behavior, and proposes `&!` be used when you want to see output (or the corresponding `Start-Job -ShowOutput` parameter.

I changed `-ShowInHost` to `ShowOutput`, and renamed `Show-/Hide-JobData` as `Show-/Hide-JobOutput` so that they are all consistent. I prefer `Output` as the suffix over `Progress` because this isn't the same as `Write-Progress`, and I don't want to confuse the two. I prefer `Output` as the suffix over `Status` because job status is a different thing.

I believe making this consistent on `Output` will set expectations appropriately and avoid confusion. If you disagree, please let me know.

In my theory that tool still needs to obey the same rule: it can't just expand the .text/.rodata/.data section, otherwise it has to move the section following it. The only section it can expand is .bss, where it place the code and reprotect the .bss to executable. Skimming over their code, it seems it indeed does it in this way. .bss section is not stored in .code, and [it is automatically expanded according to exheader](https://github.com/citra-emu/citra/blob/0c6c1d49d7e62d486bf88f800bb4d24eb00afbd2/src/core/loader/ncch.cpp#L94), therefore there is no need to expand the size here.

The reason I am particular concerned at this part is it adds extra logic that 3DS doesn't have, and it can be something we would forget to change if we change some related thing in the future. One that comes into my mind is FIRM module loading, which has a very different code section size calculation rule (they apply additional alignment/padding between sections). If we include this code here, and we want to change FIRM module loading in the future, we would have to change two separate places to make this work.

If the expression were ```(m.x + m.y)**2```, then the 3rd and 4th order terms would be zero. As written, this is a 4th order polynomial. Thus, the 4th order taylor series expansion should be exact, which is essentially what this test checks. In fact, that is what all of these tests are doing. This is why I focused on testing polynomials. With polynomials, we can test that a taylor series of the same order as the polynomial returns the same polynomial. It is not terribly easy to test that the expressions generated are exactly what I expect without writing a custom walker. However, it is very unlikely that the value of the original expression and the value of the taylor series expansion will be identical at all of the points being tested unless the expressions are identical. In my opinion, that makes these very good tests.

Keep in mind that, in the current implemenation, the higher order taylor series expansions of multivariate expressions are very ugly. This is because the implementation is rather naive, and no simplification is done. For example, the 4th order taylor series expansion for 

```(m.x*m.y)**2``` 

is 

```2.25*(x - 0.5) + 0.75*(y - 1.5) + 0.5625 + 0.5*(x - 0.5)*(4.5*(x - 0.5) + 3.0*(y - 1.5)) + 0.5*(y - 1.5)*(3.0*(x - 0.5) + 0.5*(y - 1.5)) + 0.16666666666666666*(x - 0.5)*(x - 0.5)*(6.0*(y - 1.5)) + 0.16666666666666666*(x - 0.5)*(y - 1.5)*(6.0*(x - 0.5) + 2.0*(y - 1.5)) + 0.16666666666666666*(y - 1.5)*(x - 0.5)*(6.0*(x - 0.5) + 2.0*(y - 1.5)) + 0.16666666666666666*(y - 1.5)*(y - 1.5)*(2.0*(x - 0.5)) + 0.041666666666666664*(x - 0.5)*(x - 0.5)*(y - 1.5)*(4*(y - 1.5)) + 0.041666666666666664*(x - 0.5)*(y - 1.5)*(x - 0.5)*(4*(y - 1.5)) + 0.041666666666666664*(x - 0.5)*(y - 1.5)*(y - 1.5)*(4*(x - 0.5)) + 0.041666666666666664*(y - 1.5)*(x - 0.5)*(x - 0.5)*(4*(y - 1.5)) + 0.041666666666666664*(y - 1.5)*(x - 0.5)*(y - 1.5)*(4*(x - 0.5)) + 0.041666666666666664*(y - 1.5)*(y - 1.5)*(x - 0.5)*(4*(x - 0.5))```

 If you simplify it, it does turn out to be ```x**2*y**2```.

Mutations in particular are probably very similar in API and UI, true. Not aware of a way to bring these together but open to suggestions. Reading endpoints (index, show) though will often be different as the API has a narrow focus while the UI may display many different things at once.

To answer your first question, you can use resource nesting:

```elixir
resources "/networks", NetworkController do
  resources "/collaboration", CollaborationController, only: [:create, :delete]
end

resources "/podcasts", NetworkController do
  resources "/collaboration", CollaborationController, only: [:create, :delete]
end

# ...
```

That generates routes like `DELETE  /networks/:network_id/collaborations/:id`

In that case you can have one generic `CollaborationController` and match on the params, as one will have a `network_id` in the request and the other one `podcast_id`. etc. `mix phx.routes` is helpful to see what routes witch what paramters are generated.

We can use here a utility we have to identify missing `__init__.py` files: 

https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/c26f374caadc91de631a98ff540854ff923d2a2d/src/python/pants/backend/python/subsystems/pex_build_util.py#L79-L92

The function works like this:
```
$ ./pants repl src/python/pants/backend/python/subsystems

>>> from pants.backend.python.subsystems.pex_build_util import identify_missing_init_files
>>> identify_missing_init_files(["hello/world/test.py"])
{'hello/__init__.py', 'hello/world/__init__.py'}
```

So, here you would call  `identify_missing_init_files([target_workdir])`, then iterate over the result to create an empty `__init__.py` file.

--

In addition to the above change, it would be great to use `pathlib.Path` to simplify the creation of the file. Specifically, you could do this:

```python
for missing_init in identify_missing_init_files([target_workdir]):
  Path(missing_init).touch()
```

See https://docs.python.org/3/library/pathlib.html#pathlib.Path.touch.

No, that's correct :) This is how curly brackets are escaped. `({{|}})` is equivalent to `({{)|(}})` (except that it captures things correctly). In the visual spec, there is this example: ```xquery

Here is a query.

{{ $b/title }}

Here is the result of the query.

{ $b/title } ``` This would produce the following XML (assuming `$b/title` returns the string `"X"`): ```html

Here is a query.

{ $b/title }

Here is the result of the query.

X ``` So `{{` and `}}` are text in this example, just like the `$b/title` inside it is.

There is a pattern I have seen using `with` and "tagged" conditions that is a bit verbose but linearizes otherwise nested conditional if/case/with constructs:

```elixir
with {:permission, true} <- {:permission, has_permission(actor, subject, :manage)},
     {:set, :ok} <- {:set, Editor.Permission.set_permission(user, subject, permission)} do
  {:ok, collaborator}
else
  {:permission, _} -> @not_authorized_match
  {:set, _} -> raise {:error, :could_not_set_permission}
end
```

You code the "happy path" in the with but tag each line with a unique tuple. Then you can check in the `else` match which line failed and return the error accordingly.

That's a much better looking way of doing it. > I believe that it is important to discourage coding to the tests

Hmmm, I'm not sure I fully agree with this statement to be honest. Exercism has always structured the exercises in typical TDD fashion, where each new test case is intended to "break" the existing code, and require changes to the code to make it pass. The TDD mindset is that you should do the minimal amount of work to make the code pass; it is up to the tests to force an extensive implementation that covers all cases.

That being said, I do feel that you have a very valid point, where we shouldn't discourage a student from using valid defensive coding practices. I like your suggestion (especially the bit about considering the difference in behavior). The only thing I would maybe change is the "For variety" bit. Maybe we could use `As an alternative`?

My reading of `cmake/OpenCogGuile.cmake` is that it does nothing with shared libraries. It only does some copying of scm files. They all just assume that their shared library will be available. There are no paths to get out of sync, because they are currently never configured! We cross our fingers and hope the library is somewhere in the RPATH chain, or in LTDL_LIBRARY_PATH (the former doesn't work with RUNPATH, the latter mixes up install and build dirs).

Having said that, it makes sense to put the configuration of shared library dependencies as an optional argument to `ADD_GUILE_MODULE`. And would simplify updating downstream projects.

I'm not a cmake expert and it'll take me a while to figure out how to run `CONFIGURE_FILE` *after* all the scm modules have been defined and stored their paths. I'll see how I go.

Should we be documenting Anaconda by default?

Anaconda includes quite a few packages not used in building SciPy and leads to a reasonable large download, which may be a barrier to users with slow internet connections. See this [NumPy mailing list](http://numpy-discussion.10968.n7.nabble.com/how-much-does-binary-size-matter-td46885.html#a46886) discussion. Note that they are discussing a **16mb** download. The Anaconda installer on its own is ~650mb.

Second, when using the ``apt`` machinery, a user who can't (or doesn't want to) use Anaconda must specify the requires packages individually. In that case having a reference of the required packages will be useful (plus whenever I rebuild SciPy I can simply copy and paste the requirements)

in 1990 it might have been ok to create a single-threaded api, but it feels a bit off nowadays - except perhaps that nim multi-threading is too broken to use for now ;) `addQuitProc` is pretty useless in general though - if the process is terminating, there's no need to release the context really as the OS will take care of it, and if it's aborting it won't run. 

Destroying contexts is needed mostly if you're doing a proper API that allows you to control the lifetime of the library or use it in multiple parts of your application independently and without leaks (ie plugins or modules that don't know about each other).

threadvar comes with its own problems including the point / time of initialization, and no (easy) way to coordinate release - what happens if you want to pass an decimal between threads?

```SQL
WHERE whitelist.enabled = 1 AND (whitelist_by_group.group_id IS NULL OR domain_groups.enabled = 1)
```

If we're aiming for a Feature subclassing API which is flexible enough to implement equivalents to the built-in features then it would be need at least a `protected` API.  But we'd be providing it for the purpose of allowing users to create their own features, rather than just exposing internal details purely for access by the test suite.

User-created features are useful for at least two categories of things:

* general purpose features which xapian-letor doesn't yet implement but would be candidates for merging into a future version.  It's useful (but not vital) to be able to implement these without having to patch and rebuild xapian-letor.  In some cases these would ideally need access to more stats so would need changes to xapian-letor anyway (e.g. if I wanted to add a feature which used the number of unique terms in the document).

* features which are specific to a particular application - for example if I'm implementing letor for search in an online store I might want to try adding features for price, number of sales, physical size of item, etc.

Many of the second category of features could actually be implemented without access to the stats (they'd probably either pull data from value slots in the Xapian DB or by querying some external data store).

The <normalmap> node is a math node that allows for a normal vector defined in one space to be transformed into another space. Inputs:
- "in" : input normal vector
- "space" : the input space for the normal. Possible options are "object" for object space and "tangent" for tangent space.
- "scale" : the normal can be scaled (offset) by a given multiplier.
- "normal" and "tangent". Two vectors from which a bitangent vector is computed to form the basis used for transformation. By default the vectors are in world space, meaning the output vector will be in world space.
```
  <nodedef name="ND_normalmap" node="normalmap" type="vector3" nodegroup="math">
    <input name="in" type="vector3" value="0.5, 0.5, 1.0"/> 
    <parameter name="space" type="string" value="tangent" enum="object,tangent"/>
    <input name="scale" type="float" value="1.0"/>
    <input name="normal" type="vector3" defaultgeomprop="Nworld"/>
    <input name="tangent" type="vector3" defaultgeomprop="Tworld"/>
  </nodedef>
```
Below is an example of this utility being used to read in a image containing tangent space normals and outputting world space normals scaled by a factor of 1.5.
```
  <image name="normal_image" type="vector3" colorspace="Raw">
    <parameter name="file" type="filename" value="normal_image.png" />
  </image>
  <normalmap name="surface_normals" type="vector3">
    <input name="in" type="vector3" nodename="normal_image" />
    <input name="scale" type="float" value="1.5" />
  </normalmap>
```

## Step 4: Add a page title Your web page is beginning to take shape! HTML and body tags are important, but their effect isn't too visible. Next, we'll make a visible change, by giving your page a title. Your page's title will show up on the title bar in your web browser, or as the title of any tabs you've got open. The title is used in all sorts of other places! ![a screenshot of the title on a browser tab](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16547949/41006294-e990b476-68ee-11e8-8cfa-67c72c132095.png) The title tag looks like this: ```html I am a title! ``` But the title tag must be inside of a head tag. By now, you've noticed that tags have a hierarchical structure. In our prior example, the `html` tag was the parent of the `body` tag. In a similar fashion, the `head` tag will be the parent of the `title` tag, like so: ```html I am a title! ``` Finally, the `head` and `title` tags, will be children of the `html` tag, but siblings of the `body` tag. ```html I am a title! Some content. ``` ### :keyboard: Activity: Give your page a title Apply this suggested change, or follow the instructions below if you'd like to type out the code manually. ```suggestion My awesome web page ``` 1. Write out a title after the opening `title` tag. 1. Place a closing `` tag and a closing `` tag after your new title, but before the `body` tag. 1. This should basically be correct except you don't need to allocate the memory yourself. So you should be able to declare a pointer like `uint8_t *mapped_memory`, then pass the address of that to `wgpu_device_create_buffer_mapped` (using `&mapped_memory`):

    uint8_t *memory;

    WGPUBufferId staging_buffer = wgpu_device_create_buffer_mapped(device,
        &(WGPUBufferDescriptor){.size = numbers_length,
            .usage = WGPUBufferUsage_MAP_READ | WGPUBufferUsage_TRANSFER_DST |
                WGPUBufferUsage_TRANSFER_SRC},
        &mapped_memory);

Afterwards `mapped_memory` will point to the mapped memory (but only while it is mapped). Then you can copy data into `mapped_memory`, and later unmap it.

```
@Advice.Origin Method method
``` 

```
@Advice.Origin("#m") String methodName
```

Since you're processing *relative* paths here, I don't think you need to validate that it has a prefix. The cases we should support are:
`/foo/bar`  <-- not entirely absolute on windows but close enough. You can check for it with the `has_root()` method.
`c:/foo/bar`  <-- that's where the prefix matters. We want either a drive letter + `has_root() == true`, or nothing at all.
'a/relative/path`  <-- for relative paths there shouldn't be any prefix. If there is then we get `C:a/relative/path` and that's *not* what we want to support.

In math you ought to somehow avoid being able to do any computation at all here. Both sides are some continuous reparameterization of the function defined on [0, 3] by f, then g, then h, and whatever those reparameterizations [0, 1] -> [0, 3] are, you can linearly interpolate between them to define a homotopy which is constant at the endpoints. I'm not sure how easy it is to express that to Lean though (and this is the point where I gave up on this kind of approach when I tried this).

Same comments, but doable for sure, apply to `comp_id` and `comp_inv`. And even for definitions like `symm`, maybe it's better to define them in terms of what I called `congr_right` (or possibly `congr_left`, Scott has caused me to lose all sense of direction). If you have access to Switzer's book Algebraic Topology I think this stuff is explained properly in Chapter 2 there--all these basic constructions are induced by structure on the unit interval (or more generally, on a cylinder functor, as in https://github.com/rwbarton/lean-homotopy-theory/blob/lean-3.4.2/src/homotopy_theory/formal/cylinder/definitions.lean).

For `x::Matrix` that is column-wise, `~ MvNormal(zeros(2), 1)`, the user would need to do `x ~ MvNormal(zeros(2), 1)`. This is case 1 in the proposal given below https://github.com/TuringLang/Turing.jl/pull/819#issuecomment-504994714. This will be covered by the `dist::Distribution` method (to be changed in this PR) not the `dist::Vector{<:Distribution}` method which this PR currently modifies.

`x ~ [Fill(MvNormal(zeros(2), 1), 2)]` should arguably error. The rhs is a `Vector{<:Vector{<:Distribution}}`. I think we can should only support `Array{<:Distribution}`. This can be through `map` semantics  using `lhs ~ rhs::Array{<:Distribution}` where `size(lhs) == size(rhs)` (otherwise error), case 3 in the proposal below. Or it can be through broadcast semantics using `.~` which broadcasts `lhs` and `rhs` to matching sizes, case 2 in the proposal below.

Sort is a good idea, and I have seen tkinter users who have wanted it in tkinter.

This code feels wrong to me for a couple reasons:

- You are modifying `self.rows` in a loop that loops over `self.rows`. That is generally a bad idea. For example, what does this code print?

    ```
    stuff = ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']
    for thing in stuff:
        stuff.remove(thing)
    print(stuff)
    ```

    The problem is that Python uses an index variable for looping internally, so it does `stuff.remove(stuff[0])`, `stuff.remove(stuff[1])` etc until `stuff[the index]` gives `IndexError`. The list shrinks as items are removed from it, which screws up the indexes; first this removes `a` (element 0), and then because the list is `['b', 'c', 'd', 'e']` it removes `'c'` (element 1), and then the list is `['b', 'd', 'e']` and it removes `'e'` (element 2). A simple solution is to loop over `stuff.copy()`.

- There is a similar issue with `self.rows.move`. Once an element has been moved, its index may still change as other items are moved. For example, if the rows are `[A, B, C]` after moving row `B` to index 1, and row `A` is moved to index 2, then `B` will be at index 0.

Here is a simpler example code that does not sort a list correctly:

```python3
import random

stuff = [7, 3, 2, 5, 6, 1, 8, 4]

def move(old, new):
    value = stuff[old]
    del stuff[old]
    stuff.insert(new, value)

sorted_stuff = sorted(stuff)
for old, value in enumerate(stuff):
    move(old, sorted_stuff.index(value))

print(stuff)
```

I would try something like this

```python3
for row in reversed(sorted_rows):
    self.rows.move(self.rows.index(row), 0)
```

This moves each item to the beginning, moving all the previously moved items after it. This is not ideal either, and it will create a *lot* of moves. There is probably a better way to do this, but at least the `move` method should be implemented with Tk's `move` command (search for `pathname move` in ttk_treeview manual page).

I think it's fine if you delete `sort` from this pull request and let me or someone else add it :)

We've packaged a bunch of libraries at work using conan + CMake and we normally have the `Find*.cmake` script create an imported target and add all dependencies in there. This works great and lets you have all dependencies defined per target rather than having to remember to link with your dependencies' dependencies. We do something like

```cmake
add_library(foo INTERFACE IMPORTED)
set_target_properties(foo PROPERTIES
    INTERFACE_INCLUDE_DIRECTORIES ${FOO_INCLUDE_DIRS}
    INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES "${FOO_LIBRARY};dep1;dep2;..."
)
```

Then you just import the library and link to it, ignoring dependencies (e.g. via `find_package` and `target_link_libraries`).

This is good for the first version of a combiner. But in the future it would be awesome to have "strategies" for setting, getting and deleting values.

For example:
- When setting, make it a blocking call until the quickest store has a value, then return with the function but keep setting to the other store in the background, and call a given callback function (or notify me via given channel) when an error occurs in the background goroutine.
- When setting, block all calls and only return when all are finished
- When getting, I only want the fastest answer, cancel all other operations (we might need to introduce a context object for this)
- When getting and using 3 stores, wait for all operations, then compare their values and return an error if one of them is different
- When getting and using 3 stores, wait for all operations, then compare their values and return an error if _the majority_ of them is different. If the majority is the same then "trust" this majority and call `Set` in the background to the minority of Stores with "wrong" values and overwrite them with the "correct" ones
- ...

I'd love to discuss the usefulness of these strategies. Maybe that's something for a new enhancement issue.

Regarding 407: It is an *HTTP* error certainly, but it is *not* an exceptional state of the calling REST application. The application cannot know that the server expects authentication, so it sends the request. The server answers 407, so the application knows *now* that it needs to ask the user for credentials, and will request a second time. This is more like a *login handshake* than handling an actual *programming error*. Hence, no need for an *exception*, but possibly a need for some kind of new API (like a callback asking for credentials).

In one of your later comments you state that it is enough to test that the delegation happens to `comparables` (and `objects`, I assume). There are already tests which verify that the default comparator is `ChronoLocalDateTimeComparator` (`LocalDateTimeAssert_defaultComparator_Test`), and though the comparator is used in this assertion, it is not possible to use objects with type other than `LocalDateTime` as parameter, so the comparator is not utilized to its full extent.

```
LocalDateTime now = LocalDateTime.now();

assertThat(now).isEqualTo(inJapanese); // succeed
assertThat(inJapanese).isEqualTo(now); // fails
```

``````````
On 28/06/2019 23:08, Junio C Hamano wrote:
> Phillip Wood <phillip.wood123@gmail.com> writes:
> 
>>>> I wonder if users understand that '-x' is "an interctive rebase".
>>>> The documentation can read both ways, and one of these may want to
>>>> be clarified.
>>>>
>>>> 	-x <cmd>, --exec <cmd>
>>>> 	...
>>>> 	This uses the --interactive machinery internally, but it can
>>>> 	be run without an explicit --interactive.
>>>>
>>>> Is it saying that use of interactive machinery is an impelementation
>>>> detail the users should not concern themselves (in which case, the
>>>> message given to "die()" above is misleading---not a new problem
>>>> with this patch, though)?  Is it saying "-x" makes it plenty clear
>>>> that the user wants interactive behaviour, so the users do not need
>>>> to spell out --interactive in order to ask for it (in which case,
>>>> "die()" message is fine, but "... internally, but ..." is
>>>> misleading)?
>>>
>>> Hmm. What would you think about:
>>>
>>>     		die(_("--reschedule-failed-exec requires --exec or --interactive"));
> 
> I was leaning towards admitting that the use of the interactive
> machinery in "-x" is not merely an implementation detail and fixing
> the documentation, leaving the die() message in the patch as-is.

I'd really like to try and hide that as much as possible from users - 
it's just confusing. (though sometimes we can't)
> But ...
> 
>> I was wondering about requiring --exec with --reschedule-failed-exec
>> rather than checking is_interactive() as that would be easier to
>> understand.
> 
> ... I find this a reasonable way to think about the issue.  The
> option only matters when we are doing "--exec".  And the usual
> convenience measure we'd use, i.e. with --reschedule-failed-exec we
> consider that we are implicitly in --exec mode, would not work
> because there is no default "command" to be executed.
 >
>> One potential problem is if someone has an alias that
>> always sets --reschedule-failed-exec but does not always add --exec to
>> the command line.
> 
> Such a use case would be hitting this die() already without this
> topic, wouldn't it?  In which case we can say there is no "someone"
> with such an alias.

It depends what else the alias includes, if it also includes 
-i/-k/-r/--signoff then it wont have been dying but will if we start 
requiring --exec and they don't set that.

Best Wishes

Phillip
``````````

After you mentioned that we are using `if constexpr` I was curious how our project was even compiling.

Turns out that even though we are compiling with `-std=c++14` the XCode version of clang is simply emitting `warning: constexpr if is a C++17 extension [-Wc++17-extensions]`.

Our project runs on a linux distro that only has gcc 6.3 and `if constexpr` was added in 7 so that got me concerned. However I don't think it is a problem since `if constexpr` is evaluated at compile time and the invalid branches are always removed if it is used within a template. Therefore there is no new code that it would have to reference the gcc lib.

I think the same will be true for structured bindings since it is just syntactic sugar rather than any actual new logic. You may not need to add a work around for my case.

At the end of `fix_maybe_exec_rustc`, there is a fall-through for all other dependencies.  `args.rustc` gets used down there, too (which in this case would be clippy-driver, which we don't want).

So, looking closer, my thought is that `BuildConfig::rustc_wrapper` could be changed to run for primary crates only. It looks like these things have evolved independently over time, and it's not clear if it must work the way it does now, but I don't see why it should. The only users appears to be clippy and fix, and both of them only want to run against the primary crates. `fix` appears to do a bunch of dancing around whether or not something is primary, but in the end, non-primary units only fall through to the end of `fix_maybe_exec_rustc` to call rustc, so I don't see that it is necessary in any way.

"Primary" is defined as the units created by `generate_targets`.  There is a method `Context::is_primary_package` to determine if a unit is primary or not.

The `Compilation` struct will probably need to be reworked a little to support deciding which process to use.  I would also move the `rustfix_diagnostic_server` code in `Compilation::new` to the `fix` function in `fix.rs`, since it already has access to a `ProcessBuilder` (I think when this was originally written, it did not work that way).

Then I think the decision on which wrapper to use would go in [`prepare_rustc`](https://github.com/rust-lang/cargo/blob/143aaed0eedda82f6684637ba1bf2d69b24c7799/src/cargo/core/compiler/mod.rs#L591-L601).  Perhaps it could pass a bool to `Compilation::rustc_process` to tell it is a primary unit? Whatever seems cleanest here, I'm not sure.

[These lines](https://github.com/rust-lang/cargo/blob/143aaed0eedda82f6684637ba1bf2d69b24c7799/src/cargo/core/compiler/mod.rs#L183-L185) could then be removed. And all of the checks for `primary_package` in `fix.rs` could be removed.

>May I ask what prompted to change from Big Endian to Little Endian?

The endianess is still the same, I just swapped the *bits* (version) from starting from left to start from the right. The byte order is still the same as before.

I've changed it in reverse order because usually one shifts bits to the right and it allows us to check whether a position's bit was set by comparing it with `1` instead of `0b10000000` (which makes more sense imho)

1. "Unified" errors representation for all microservices of the app is a good idea in general (yes, it is not actually "unified" across all "Kyripay" services, but would be great)
2. Existing MVC abstractions usually expose message + stacktrace which may contain sensitive data and may disclose technical details about implementation through public API which is unwanted
3. Depending on Exception class and the "abstraction" that handles it  - responses may be quite different -> representation is not unified.
For example, `javax.validation.ConstraintViolationException` thrown by Service is handled automatically as INTERNAL_ERROR, and response contains useless stacktrace but doesn't contain list of violations. That's why I'd prefer to build error messages manually.

> Done to avoid breaking changes, although it is a bit awkward.

Yes, and this only hides the breaking change by turning it into a runtime error. I've been thinking about other possible approaches:

1. introduce a sub-interface and require a cast (as we've done in other cases). The problem is that this doesn't scale well: we add `ExtendedProductHelper` now but what if we need more methods in the next version? `ExtendedExtendedProductHelper`?
2. Accept the breaking change and document it, on the assumption that clients probably don't implement this interface. The problem is in the "probably"; also, it's a slippery slope.
3. Don't add those methods to `EntityHelper`. Instead, generate the query directly from the method generators. For SELECT we already have `selectStart()`; for DELETE we have to duplicate the whole method, but it's not huge either.

    We won't make those queries available to users through the interface (e.g. for custom query providers), but they're not that hard to rewrite from scratch anyway.

My vote goes to 3.

The "non" is a tough one. Pierre obviously speaks in a heavily French-accented English, e.g. the "little"/"leetle" and his "the" definitely starts with a Z. The complicated part with "non" is that in French, the second N in "non" is silent. So a French guy saying "non" in French ("non" is the French word for "no") vs. saying "no" with a French accent is practically identical.

I think whoever made the subtitles originally did a decent job making the subtitles read as French-accented, and "non" is a good way to represent that. "Leetle" and "wheech" are maybe a bit weaker because a non-English speaker might not be able to identify what words those are supposed to be. But "non", I personally think is good.

The main limitation of that approach of hiding the context is that for multi-threading you need one context per thread, but it's fine to start with single-threaded support and redirect people who need multi-threading to the low-level API.

Alternatively there is a `getContext` proc that checks if the current thread as a context already allocated, if yes retrieves it if no create one.
